cs.CG, cs.DS, cs.DM, cs.NA, cs.GT. 

The paper deals with computational geometry, specifically the problem of stabbing pairwise intersecting disks in the plane. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The algorithms presented in the paper involve data structures and probabilistic analysis, which suggest that it could also belong to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.NA (Numerical Analysis). The paper also mentions a construction that cannot be stabbed by three points, which could fall under cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory). Finally, the use of probabilistic analysis and the mention of expected time complexity suggest that it could also belong to cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics).
